(1671, 1, '2012-08-23 13:59:05', '2012-08-23 10:59:05', '<p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">To maintain a worklife balance, promote health awareness, and eliminate poor work habits, the Al Rushaid Construction Company Ltd. (ARCC) launched its Fitness and Wellness Program.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The program entitled, "Walk, Skip, and Jump for Health" attracted hundreds of health aficionados during its kick-off last September 16, 2011 at the ARCC Jubail Main Camp. The program started with opening remarks from Mr. Romulo B. Lazaro (Senior Administration Manager), who emphasized the importance of being healthy and fit. He encouraged all personnel to participate in the company''s initiative. "We designed this concept for an important reason and that is to make each of you active and live healthiereveryday," Lazaro said.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The members of the Executive Management lead by Mr. Mercado T. Magno (Vice President and General Manager for Operations) and Norman K. Macapagal (Senior Vice President) were fully supportive of the program. They stressed on the value of having a healthy mind, body, and spirit. "Health is wealth. I hope through the introduction of this Fitness and Wellness Campaign, we can sustain high morale of our employees, increase participation not only in number but in sincerity so they can reduce stress and lower the risk of serious health problems," Macapagal explained.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">"Let us all enjoy, go out, and have fun. Make use of this program to ease your boredom. While we are getting involved in this wonderful undertaking, your families back home need you as much as we need you here in the ARCC Saudi Arabia Operation," Magno said.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The program was declared open by Joey J. Rosal (ARCC Senior Manager for Personnel Services) and was hosted by Peter B. Lomboz.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The three-month "Walk, Skip, and Jump for Health" is a group competition exclusively for employees only. Prior to the opening, each employee gathered in the center court for callisthenics. At the end of the program, a charity Fun-Run will be organized in order to draw more participants and achieve its goals. The event will be held simultaneously in all ARCC camps and project locations.</p>', 'ARCC: Fitness & Wellness Program', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1659-revision-4', '', '', '2012-08-23 13:59:05', '2012-08-23 10:59:05', '', 1659, 'http://192.168.8.59/arcc/?p=1671', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1672, 1, '2012-08-23 14:17:44', '2012-08-23 11:17:44', '<p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">To maintain a worklife balance, promote health awareness, and eliminate poor work habits, the Al Rushaid Construction Company Ltd. (ARCC) launched its Fitness and Wellness Program.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The program entitled, "Walk, Skip, and Jump for Health" attracted hundreds of health aficionados during its kick-off last September 16, 2011 at the ARCC Jubail Main Camp. The program started with opening remarks from Mr. Romulo B. Lazaro (Senior Administration Manager), who emphasized the importance of being healthy and fit. He encouraged all personnel to participate in the company''s initiative. "We designed this concept for an important reason and that is to make each of you active and live healthiereveryday," Lazaro said.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The members of the Executive Management lead by Mr. Mercado T. Magno (Vice President and General Manager for Operations) and Norman K. Macapagal (Senior Vice President) were fully supportive of the program. They stressed on the value of having a healthy mind, body, and spirit. "Health is wealth. I hope through the introduction of this Fitness and Wellness Campaign, we can sustain high morale of our employees, increase participation not only in number but in sincerity so they can reduce stress and lower the risk of serious health problems," Macapagal explained.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">"Let us all enjoy, go out, and have fun. Make use of this program to ease your boredom. While we are getting involved in this wonderful undertaking, your families back home need you as much as we need you here in the ARCC Saudi Arabia Operation," Magno said.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The program was declared open by Joey J. Rosal (ARCC Senior Manager for Personnel Services) and was hosted by Peter B. Lomboz.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The three-month "Walk, Skip, and Jump for Health" is a group competition exclusively for employees only. Prior to the opening, each employee gathered in the center court for callisthenics. At the end of the program, a charity Fun-Run will be organized in order to draw more participants and achieve its goals. The event will be held simultaneously in all ARCC camps and project locations.</p>', 'ARCC: Fitness & Wellness Program', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1659-revision-5', '', '', '2012-08-23 14:17:44', '2012-08-23 11:17:44', '', 1659, 'http://192.168.8.59/arcc/?p=1672', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1673, 1, '2012-08-23 13:46:24', '2012-08-23 10:46:24', '<p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;"><strong>The Earth-Breaking Ceremony of the Manifa Training Center and Plant Model for the Saudization Program</strong> was inaugurated recently with Mr. Norman K. Macapagal (SVP – KSA Operations) and Al Rushaid Petroleum Investment Company’s (ARPIC) Hossam Kh. Al Rahyyem (VP – Administration and Industries Support) with Khalid A. Al Abdul Aziz (Group Human Resources Manager). Joining them in the affair were the Executive Management from Saudi Aramco, Mohammed A. Abdul Karim Manifa Development Program Manager) and Mohammed A. Al Mana (Senior Project Manager of Manifa Program).</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The vision of using a Plant Model for the Saudi Personnel Enhancement and Skills Development Program was originally designed by the Manifa Project Manager Edwin T. Paragas. He saw the need of hands-on training so that the Saudi workers’ skill and confidence will be developed prior to the actual work at the project site. It is their objective to improve the performance of the Saudi workforce through these training facilities and by adopting Saudi Aramco standards.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">Upon completion of the program, the participants will be given a Saudi Aramco Certification Qualifications.</p>', 'Manifa Training Center and Plant Model', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1654-revision-4', '', '', '2012-08-23 13:46:24', '2012-08-23 10:46:24', '', 1654, 'http://192.168.8.59/arcc/?p=1673', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1674, 1, '2012-08-23 13:46:43', '2012-08-23 10:46:43', '<p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;"><strong>EEI Corporation ’s subsidiary in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia , Al Rushaid Construction Company, LTD.</strong>, completed several key project milestones in the Saudi Aramco Manifa Utilities, Storage, and Shipping Facilities Project. As of September, 2011, the project was 52.79% accomplished, 2.65% ahead of schedule.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The Manifa Development Program, an important increment in Saudi Arabia’s Capital Program is designed to increase petroleum output in response to increasing world energy demand. This offshore field is designed to produce 900,000 barrels per day (bpd) of extra capacity to Saudi Arabia’s oil output. This will also produce 120 million scfd of sour gas, 50,000 bpd of condensate, and 950,000 bpd of produced water. The central processing utility of the Manifa Offshore Oil Field also aims to process one billion cubic feet per day of natural gas.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The significant highlight of the project is the completion of Pipe Rack Structures (with a total weight of 6197 tons). The installation of miscellaneous structures is still ongoing.<p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">As far as mechanical works is concerned, 156 out of 175 sets of equipment (equivalent to 92.83% progress) have already been installed. The work progress for welded-type pipes is already at 58.80% progress, while progress for the flangetype pipes is at 42.20%.<p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The total instrument cables that have been pulled is 121,040 out of 355,900 linear meters, (lm). 82.13% or of the total cable trays have been installed while 229,482 out of 532,025 lm of the total cables have already been pulled out.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">Painting Works is already 9.46% accomplished while Insulation Works is schedule to start in October.<p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">ARCC will perform 65% of the total works for the Manifa Central Processing Facilities (also known as Package 2), which includes Mechanical, Electrical, and Instrumentation Works for the Manifa Central Producing Facilities and its associated plants as well as the Crude Storage and Shipping Pumps, Water Oil Separation Plant, Water Injection Plant, Reverse Osmosis Utility, and Ponds and West Manifold Facilities.<p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The project started last September 15, 2010 and has an on-site workforce of about 1,667 with 4,122,406 recorded manhours without Lost Time Accident.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">This plant, in which Japan Gas Corporation and ARCC play major roles, is of high importance to Saudi Aramco and to Saudi Arabia as well, as it will deliver the necessary feedstock for the diversification of KSA’s downstream industries.</p>', 'Manifa Project in full swing!', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1650-revision-5', '', '', '2012-08-23 13:46:43', '2012-08-23 10:46:43', '', 1650, 'http://192.168.8.59/arcc/?p=1674', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1675, 1, '2012-08-23 13:21:40', '2012-08-23 10:21:40', '<p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The SAMREF CFP Project has accomplished <strong>1 Million Manhours without Lost Time Accident</strong> as of August 22, 2011. Mr. Ron Speer, Construction Director of SAMREF CFP, is happy with ARCC’s excellent performance in carrying out the work. "<strong>We look forward to additional milestone achievements of ARCC in attaining our overall goal of ''Nobody Gets Hurt''</strong>," Speer said.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">ARCC will continue its commitment to Safety.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The current manpower level is at 1,355, with more manpower and construction equipment being mobilized weekly to support the project completion according to schedule.</p>', 'SAMREF', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1643-revision-7', '', '', '2012-08-23 13:21:40', '2012-08-23 10:21:40', '', 1643, 'http://192.168.8.59/arcc/?p=1675', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1676, 1, '2012-08-22 15:21:30', '2012-08-22 12:21:30', '<p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">Al Rushaid Construction Co. Ltd. has successfully retained is ISO 9001:2008 accreditation for another 3 years in the re-certification audit conducted last March 5-6, 2012 by T&#xDC;V NORD. Since 2006, ARCC has maintained its ISO certificaton including its transition from ISO 9000:2000 standard to ISO 9001:2008.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">ARCC is the first construction company which has attained ISO 9001 Quality Management System accreditation on 2008 standard version, and this was specially mentioned by the T&#xDC;V Nord auditors: Dr. Arshad Ali Naqvi (Auditing Manager and Lead Auditor) and Muhamed Ameen Valliyengal (QMS Auditor) during their opening meeting.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">They also said that ARCC is consistent in complying with its established Quality Management System. This consistency shows the dynamism of the organization in implementing, following, and monitoring its QMS with regard to the (ARCC) client''s requirements. Dr. Naqvi added that continual improvement process will be looked into during the re-certification audit.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">Present during the opening meeting at the ARCC Head Office in Al Khobar are officers of the company, headed by Norman K. Macapagal (Senior Vice President and General Manager) and Mercado T. Magno (Vice President and General Manager for Operations). Both officers echoed Dr. Naqvi''s remarks on improvement as they talked about the organizational efficiency already being implemented in the Company, including the revisions to the policies and procedures.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The Company is proud that its services meet the highest quality levels which generate total customer satisfaction. Maintaining ISO 9001 standards is a milestone and of prime importance for the entire team of QA/QC Department.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">"Getting through the re-certification audit and obtaining its approval has made ARCC more confident in delivering quality services to its customers and in return gaining respect from our existing and prospective clients, which ecentually win us more projects", according to Fortunato R. Solis, Jr. (Senior AVP- Corporate QA/QC).</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">ARCC operates in the Kingdom for the construction of major industrial facilities of Aramco, Saudi Arabia Basic Industries Corporation (SABIC) and Saudi Electric Company (SCESO). Amoung its major clients include Bechtel, TECHNIP, Worley-Parsons, JGC, MHI and Samsung.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The audit process of the first day included an interview with Top Management, Marketing, Engineering, Contracts, Procurement, Central Logistics and Administraton, Equipment / Tools, the Management Representative and Central DCS. During the second day of audit, T&#xDC;V Auditors visited ARCC''s SAMCO Acrylic Acid Plant Project in Jubail Industrial City. An introductory meeting was held wih Project Manger Ronnie Domingo and all his PMT staff. The audit started with the Project Manager and Project Control, followed by QC, Purchasing, Equipment Section and Warehouse. Assisting the T&#xDC;V NORD auditors were ARCC Management Representative [MR] Manuel C. Bisbal and QMS Lead Auditor Oliver M. Estrella, both certified by the International Registry of Certificated Auditors (IRCA).</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">During the closing meeting held at ARCC Central Training Room in Juaymah, Dr. Naqvi and his co-lead auditor Muhammed Ameen acknowledged the strengths of the Company. "You have a very good and effective training and development program, competent workforce, and most importantly strong management commitment on quality and these are the Company''s strong points," said Dr. Arshad Ali Naqvi.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">Mr. Norman K. Macapagal, Senior Vice President and General Manager extends his warmest congratulations to the entire team and said, "We know the value of having strong commitment to quality standards. We will be able to earn the respect and confidence of our clients. This re-certification will continue to prove that our operations are at par with some of the international contractors operating in the Kingdom. Quality and organizational efficiency will continue to be a trademark of ARCC, thus realizing our vision in becoming the contractor of choice."</p>', 'ARCC is ISO 9001:2008', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1446-revision-9', '', '', '2012-08-22 15:21:30', '2012-08-22 12:21:30', '', 1446, 'http://192.168.8.59/arcc/?p=1676', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1677, 1, '2012-08-18 16:43:47', '2012-08-18 13:43:47', '<p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">Al Rushaid Construction Co., Ltd. has achieved another milestone in its first ASME and National Board of Inspection Code  NBIC) stamping requirements on Saudi Polymers Company / National Chevron Philips Cracking Furnaces Boiler Feed Water Modification Works Project at Al Jubail Industrial City, Kingdom of Saudi Arabia.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The scope of work originally involves the modification of the Boiler Feed Water Coils and Headers of the Cracking Furnaces No. 41F01, 41F02 and 41F06. This means cutting the return bends on each end of the Boiler Feed Water Coils and altering the flow from an up-to-down direction to a side-toside direction. The modification of the Boiler Feed Water Coils and inlet/outlet Headers of the Cracking Furnaces is to be carried out in conjunction with ASME Section 1 Edition 2010 and NBIC (ANSI/NB23) Edition 2011. Likewise, an “R” Code direct stamp is to be placed adjacent to the original Boiler Manufacturer stamp and the Data Report will be signed by an ASME Authorized Inspector (AI) for each furnace upon completion of the modification work and the hydrostatic test.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The overall performance, competency, high productivity, and organizational efficiency put into the work by ARCC Fabrication Project Management Team, headed by Jay-Ar T. Daquel, on this project impressed the Client. The Client has awarded ARCC to perform the work of the same scope to three (3) additional cracking furnaces (Nos. 41F03, 41F05 and 41F08). The work started last October 29, 2011 and was completed on January 11, 2012, which is fifty-two (52) days ahead of contract schedule.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">“The work was tough due to the restricted and congested location, but our welders excelled, which completed the project ahead of schedule with excellent work quality and safety. Moreover, I would like to thank Hassan Al Hourani, ASME Authorized Inspector (AI) from TÜV NORD, and Nelson A. Molina, ARCC Fabrication QA/QC In-Charge, for their cooperation and exemplary inspection,” remarked Jay-Ar T. Dacquel (ARCC Fabrication In-Charge).</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">“The project attained an overall 97.51% Weld Acceptance Rate. The client was very happy and satisfied with the performance of the ARCC welders,” said Fortunato R. Solis Jr. (ARCC Sr. AVP/Corporate QA/QC).</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">“Currently, ARCC is looking for and expecting more incoming projects having ASME and NBIC stamping requirements in which ARCC is very much\r\nready and confident to mark again with another excellent performance and quality workmanship,” concluded Mercado T. Magno (ARCC VP and General Manager-Operations). Norman K. Macapagal, ARCC General Manager, expressed his deepest gratitude and warm congratulations to the Project Management Team for the job well done.</p>', 'Passes ASME and NBIC', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1461-revision-8', '', '', '2012-08-18 16:43:47', '2012-08-18 13:43:47', '', 1461, 'http://192.168.8.59/arcc/?p=1677', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1678, 1, '2012-08-22 15:16:48', '2012-08-22 12:16:48', '<p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">Last March 10, 2012, ARCC was given a Plaque by the PSA 2000/FIVES SOLIOS Carbone for being the “<strong>Most Compliant Contractor of PSA 2000 in 2011</strong>” in the Green Anode Plant and Liquid Pitch Terminal Project in Ras Az Zawr, in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia being done for the Saudi Arabian Mining Co. (Ma’aden). The plaque was given in appreciation of ARCC’s contribution to PSA 2000/FIVES SOLIOS’ achievement of being the “Best Contractor of the Year 2011” by Bechtel.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">ARCC Vice President and General Manager\r\nMercado T. Magno received the award from Michael Koch, PSA 2000/FIVES SOLIOS Site General Manager, in behalf of ARCC. During the awarding ceremony, ARCC was also commended for achieving <strong>3 Million Safe Manhours without Lost Time Incident</strong>.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">ARCC’s contract with PSA 2000/FIVES SOLIOS involves civil, structural, mechanical, and piping works for one of the facilities within the Ma’aden\r\nAluminium Smelter Plant. This aluminum smelter plant is believed to be the biggest in the world.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">ARCC’s consistency in its safety practice is seen from the fact that it was awarded “Safest Contractor” by PSA 2000/FIVES SOLIOS in May, July, and August last year. “We would like to thank Bechtel and PSA 2000/FIVES SOLIOS for this award as well as those who are involved in this project especially our workers and staff. We could not have accomplished this feat without their cooperation and support” said Magno.</p>', '3 Million Safe Manhours and Most HSE Compliant Contractor', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1469-revision-8', '', '', '2012-08-22 15:16:48', '2012-08-22 12:16:48', '', 1469, 'http://192.168.8.59/arcc/?p=1678', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1679, 1, '2012-08-23 14:16:58', '2012-08-23 11:16:58', '<p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">On March 12, 2012, the Solios Project celebrated another milestone for achieving 3,000,000 Safe Manhours without Lost Time Incident in the construction of the biggest Aluminum Smelter Plant in the world. The plant is a joint venture project of Maaden and ALCOA. </p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">ARCC is the contractor for the Civil and SMPP Erection Works.</p>', 'Aluminum Smelter Plant Project', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1474-revision-5', '', '', '2012-08-23 14:16:58', '2012-08-23 11:16:58', '', 1474, 'http://192.168.8.59/arcc/?p=1679', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1680, 1, '2012-08-18 16:44:39', '2012-08-18 13:44:39', '<p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">Last January 7, 2012, fourteen of ARCC’s top managers, which include Norman K. Macapagal (Senior Vice President and General Manager) and Mercado T. Magno (Vice President and General Manager for Operations), had the opportunity to attend the workshop on “LEAN CONSTRUCTION” War on Waste held at the EEI Corporation Head Office.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">As soon as they returned to the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, the ARCC Management showed their determination to further improve organizational efficiency by creating the G.R.O.W. (Getting Rid Of Waste) Program.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">“We cannot rest on our laurels,” Magno said during the initial leg of the echo-seminar on Lean Construction, which he conducted last March 16, 2012 at Juaymah Central Training Room. He told the twenty-one (21) Managers who attended the seminar/workshop that while ARCC has been maximizing the utilization of its resources and is greatly benefitting from it, it should not cease from finding better ways to improve its operations.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The G.R.O.W. Program focuses on eight waste areas which should be monitored and addressed in order to achieve the principles of “Lean Construction”. These eight waste areas are: correction, department inefficiency, material movement, motion, equipment breakdown, waiting, inventory, and over processing.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">During the seminar-workshop the participants showed keen interest in implementing various programs and activities as evidenced by their respective outputs during the workshop.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The second and final batch of twenty-three (23) ARCC managers likewise underwent the echo-seminar on March 30, 2012 with ARCC’s Senior Vice President and General Manager, Mr. Norman K. Macapagal as resource speaker.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">The said program shall be cascaded to the level of the Senior Staff. This will provide them vital information to successfully implement “Lean Construction” in their respective areas.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">ARCC blazes the trail towards organizational efficiency via the “G.R.O.W. Program” and shall soon get “leaner” than ever.</p>', 'ARCC: Leaner Than Ever', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1478-revision-6', '', '', '2012-08-18 16:44:39', '2012-08-18 13:44:39', '', 1478, 'http://192.168.8.59/arcc/?p=1680', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1681, 1, '2012-08-22 15:18:40', '2012-08-22 12:18:40', '<p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">Launching of the ARCC Fund Raising Drive for the SENDONG calamity victims held last December 22,2011, during the ARCC Year-end Celebration at Jubail Camp.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">As the show started, teary-eyed employees gave their donations cheerfully with a smile knowing that with their “one Riyal” they have whole-heartedly contributed will go a long way in helping the victims of SENDONG and collected seven water bottles bursting to its lid filled with donations.</p><p style="text-align: justify;text-justify: inter-word;text-indent: 40px;">Water Bottles were used to dramatically symbolize the irony that, the water (flood waters) which ravaged the Southern Philippines would be the same water (of donation) will help resuscitate the victims of the calamity.</p>', '"Isang Riyal na Tulong sa mga Sinalanta ng Baha"', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1317-revision-8', '', '', '2012-08-22 15:18:40', '2012-08-22 12:18:40', '', 1317, 'http://192.168.8.59/arcc/?p=1681', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
